Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

Circadian rhythm optimization and light exposure protocols
Sleep architecture understanding (light, deep, REM cycles)
Sleep onset latency reduction techniques
Temperature manipulation for sleep quality (Huberman/Walker protocols)
Caffeine half-life management and timing cutoffs
Blue light and screen exposure protocols
Sleep environment optimization (light, sound, temperature, bedding)
Consistent sleep-wake schedule design
Wind-down routine architecture
Sleep tracking interpretation (Oura, Whoop, Apple Watch, Fitbit)

Methodologies & Frameworks
Science: Matthew Walker's "Why We Sleep," Andrew Huberman's sleep toolkit, AASM guidelines
Protocols: Sleep restriction therapy (CBT-I based), Stimulus control, Relaxation training
Chronotype: Michael Breus's chronotype quiz (Bear, Lion, Wolf, Dolphin), Morningness-Eveningness questionnaire
Metrics: Total sleep time, Sleep efficiency (time asleep/time in bed), Sleep latency, WASO (Wake After Sleep Onset)
Environment: Temperature (18-19°C optimal), Darkness (complete), Sound (white noise or silence), Air quality
Tracking: Oura ring, Whoop, Apple Watch sleep tracking, Sleep diary (manual)

Reference Documentation
1. Huberman Sleep Toolkit
Comprehensive guide covering:
- Morning sunlight viewing within 30 min of waking (10-30 minutes)
- Afternoon sunlight viewing for circadian anchor
- Evening dim light protocol (2 hours before bed)
- Temperature drop protocol (hot shower/bath 90 min before bed creates rebound cooling)
- Caffeine cutoff: 8-10 hours before bedtime
- Supplements: Magnesium threonate, Apigenin, Theanine (with caveats)

2. Sleep Environment Guide
Complete optimization library:
- Temperature: 18-19°C (65-67°F) room temperature
- Light: Blackout curtains or sleep mask, no standby LEDs
- Sound: Consistent white/pink noise or earplugs
- Mattress and pillow: Support and comfort assessment
- Phone: Outside the bedroom or in airplane mode

3. Common Sleep Problems
Technical reference with:
- Can't fall asleep: Stimulus control, wind-down routine, cognitive offloading
- Waking at 3-4 AM: Blood sugar stability, cortisol timing, worry journal
- Not feeling refreshed: Sleep efficiency, deep sleep optimization, alcohol impact
- Weekend catch-up: Social jet lag damage, consistent schedule advocacy
- Jet lag: Light exposure timing, melatonin micro-dosing for clock shifting

Sleep Patterns
Pattern 1: The Non-Negotiable Wind-Down
90-minute pre-sleep routine:
- T-90 min: Last screen time (or blue light glasses minimum)
- T-60 min: Dim lights throughout home (warm/amber lamps only)
- T-45 min: Hot shower or bath (triggers core body temperature drop)
- T-30 min: Light reading, journaling, or gentle stretching
- T-15 min: Breathwork in bed (4-7-8 or body scan)
- T-0: Lights out at consistent time (±30 min, 7 days/week)

Pattern 2: Morning Anchor Protocol
Setting the circadian clock at wake:
- Wake at same time every day (yes, weekends too — ±30 min max)
- Sunlight exposure within 30 min of waking (10-30 min, no sunglasses)
- No caffeine for 90-120 min after waking (let adenosine clear naturally)
- Cold water on face or cold shower (optional, increases alertness)
- Light breakfast to signal daytime metabolism

Pattern 3: Sleep Rescue (Acute Insomnia)
When you can't fall asleep (20+ min awake):
- Get out of bed — do NOT lie there trying to force sleep
- Go to another room with dim light
- Do a boring, calming activity (read a physical book, not a screen)
- Return to bed ONLY when sleepy (eyes heavy, yawning)
- The bed must be associated with sleep, not frustration
- This is Stimulus Control Therapy — it works but feels wrong at first

Best Practices
Fundamentals
- Consistency is the #1 factor — same wake time every single day
- Caffeine has a 5-6 hour HALF-LIFE — 200mg at 2pm = 100mg at 8pm still in your system
- Alcohol is NOT a sleep aid — it suppresses REM sleep and fragments architecture
- Screen light after dark directly suppresses melatonin production
- The bedroom is for sleep and intimacy ONLY — no work, no doom-scrolling, no TV

Optimization
- Track sleep for 2 weeks before changing anything — data first
- Change ONE variable at a time — otherwise you can't attribute improvement
- Sleep efficiency > sleep duration — 7 focused hours beats 9 fragmented hours
- Temperature is the most underrated sleep lever — cooler is almost always better
- Wind-down routine trains Pavlovian sleep response — build it and protect it

Common Mistakes
- Sleeping in on weekends ("social jet lag") undermines the entire week
- Using phone as alarm = phone in bedroom = temptation to scroll
- "I'll just rest my eyes" on the couch at 9pm = destroyed sleep pressure
- Exercising within 2 hours of bedtime (for most people increases arousal)
- Napping after 3pm — steals from nighttime sleep pressure

